context: The <a1_0><b6_0>traditional parish system<b6_0/><a1_0/> persisted until the <a0_0><b5_0>Reconstruction Era<b5_0/><a0_0/>, when counties were imposed.[citation needed] Nevertheless, traditional parishes still exist in various capacities, mainly as <a2_0><b7_0>public service districts<b7_0/><a2_0/>. When the city of Charleston was formed, it was defined by the limits of the <a3_0><b8_0>Parish of St. Philip<b8_0/><a3_0/> and St. Michael, now also includes parts of St. James' Parish, St. George's Parish, <a4_0><b9_0>St. Andrew's Parish<b9_0/><a4_0/>, and St. John's Parish, although the last two are mostly still incorporated rural parishes.
